PUH-BrianMartell the Bondi accretion rate is the classic formula for how much gas a black hole (or in PUH, a Planck Star seed) can “suck in” when sitting in a uniform cloud of gas. It was derived by Hermann Bondi in 1952 for spherical, steady accretion onto a point mass. In PUH v15, this is crucial for how your primordial Planck Star seeds grow into galaxies: The intense lattice shear around a seed boosts the effective capture, overcoming gas entropy (pressure wants to push gas away). Standard Bondi is \dot{M} = 4\pi \rho r_B^2 c_s with Bondi radius r_B = 2GM/c_s^2 (c_s sound speed, ρ gas density). In PUH, lattice tension adds geometric “reel-in” — effective r_B larger from J(φ) shear, rate higher early (dense gas) for rapid SMBH growth (Little Red Dots).
